    <help><![CDATA[
vg giraffe is a fast, haplotype-aware read mapper to map reads to thousands of genomes embedded in a pangenome reference graph at a speed comparable to that of standard methods mapping to a single reference genome.
It supports short-read mapping and based on the configuration also long-read mapping. 

**Inputs**

* Graph: It is recommended to provide a GBZ format graph. Alternatively, an XG graph or an GBWTGraph along with a GBWT index can be used.
* Reads: Accepts Single-end, Paired-end, or Interleaved FASTQ/FASTA. It can also read and realign an existing GAM alignment file.

**Outputs**

* Graph Alignments: Output in the formats GAM, GAF, JSON, or TSV that describe alignments as paths through nodes in the graph.
* Linear Alignments: For output in the formats SAM, BAM, and CRAM, vg giraffe will surject the graph-based alignments onto the nearest linear reference paths embedded in the graph. **Note:** Older GBZ/GBWT graphs might not contain reference paths, which are required for surjection (e.g., if they were created with a vg version older than 1.37.0). Additionally, surjecting can sometimes cause poor performance. To avoid missing reference paths and performance issues, it is recommended to provide a compatible XG graph alongside the input graph in the output options.

-----

**Read More**

* Mapping short reads: https://github.com/vgteam/vg/wiki/Mapping-short-reads-with-Giraffe
* Mapping long reads: https://github.com/vgteam/vg/wiki/Mapping-long-reads-with-Giraffe
* Best practices: https://github.com/vgteam/vg/wiki/Giraffe-best-practices
* General vg Wiki: https://github.com/vgteam/vg/wiki/
    ]]></help>
